gs.GameStorageLocations.description: An enumeration of game storage locations.

gs.GameStorage.name: gs.GameStorage
gs.GameStorage.description:
The GameStorage helps to store different kind of game data permanentely like
a save-game or the game settings. The way how the data is stored depends on
the platform. For example: If the game runs in a web-browser the data is stored
the internal local storage of the web-browser but if the game runs locally the
data is stored on disk.

All object are stored as JSON so it is imported that the object to store can
be serialized to JSON and doesn't contain any circular references. Except for
the methods gs.GameStorage.setData and gs.GameStorage.getData since that methods
dealing with a regular string.

gs.Data.name: gs.Data
gs.Data.description:
This class is used to load Data files which are stored as JSON files in the data-folder of
the project as well as raw text data.

gs.MouseInput.name: gs.MouseInput
gs.MouseInput.description:
This class gives access to mouse or touch input. Mouse-buttons or mouse-position is automatically
mapped to touch-input on touch-devices like smartphones. For example: A single tap counts as
a left mouse-click and a double-tap counts as a right mouse-click.

gs.Input.name: gs.Input
gs.Input.description:
This class manages the input system. It needs to be initializes before any input
data can be received. It supports keyboard, mouse, touch and gamepad input data.

The input system has a set of buttons called LEFT, UP, RIGHT, DOWN, A, B, C, X, Y, Z, L, R,
START and SELECT which are emulated and available on most platforms. They are mapped
to the different input devices like to the keys of a keyboard or the buttons on a gamepad.

gs.AudioBuffer.name: gs.AudioBuffer
gs.AudioBuffer.description:
An audio buffer stream is used to stream an audio track from file. The supported
audio formats are MP3, M4A, AAC, OGG and WAV but it depends on the platforms. It is
recommended to have at least two versions for each audio file like one file in M4A and the
other file in OGG format because some platforms can only play OGG files by default while others
can only play MP3/M4A.

gs.Audio.description: This class manages the basic audio system.

gs.AudioBufferReference.name: gs.AudioBufferReference
gs.AudioBufferReference.description:
An audio buffer reference is a reference to an already existing audio buffer. It
allows to play the audio buffer independent from other references. This is useful
for sound-effects which are played very often and quickly at the same time.

params.name: audioBuffer

gs.Graphics.name: gs.Graphics
gs.Graphics.description:
This class manages the graphics system. It needs to be initializes before any
graphical operations can be executed. It initializes the necessary graphic contexts
allocates necessary resources.

It manages all graphic objects and renders them automatically on screen ordered
by the z-index of each object.

gs.TilemapRenderInfo.name: gs.TilemapRenderInfo
gs.TilemapRenderInfo.description:
A tilemap-render info holds more information about the tilemap being rendered on screen. This class is actually for internal usage only. The only exception is if you work with custom GLSL shaders.

If you want to learn more about why certain classes of the Basic Engine are hidden and not editable, read the Basic Engine chapter in Help File.

gs.RenderTask.name: gs.RenderTask
gs.RenderTask.description:
A render-task holds information about a graphic object which should be rendered on screen. This class is actually for internal usage only. The only exception is if you work with custom GLSL shaders.

If you want to learn more about why certain classes of the Basic Engine are hidden and not editable, read the Basic Engine chapter in Help File.

gs.Renderer.name: gs.Renderer
gs.Renderer.description:
The renderer is used to render graphical object on screen like images, colored rectangles, etc. It behaves
like a state-machine. So first step is to set origin, rotation-angle, color, etc. and then render
graphical objects with that settings.

params.name: context
params.description: - The graphics context.

gs.EffectInfo.name: gs.EffectInfo
gs.EffectInfo.description:
An effect-info encapsulates all necessary information to register and compile
a custom GLSL shader effect. To actually use a custom effect, it is necessary create a custom
effect class as well and derive from gs.GraphicEffect class.

params.name: data
params.description: - An optional data-bundle to create the effect-info from. Can be null.

gs.EffectCollection.name: gs.EffectCollection
gs.EffectCollection.description:
An effect collection stores all effects by name. So if you add custom effects, you
have to create an own class and inherit from this class and add your
own effects in the constructor. It is important to put the super-call at the end and not
at the beginning.

gs.Effect.name: gs.Effect
gs.Effect.description:
A class to handle Open/GLSL shader-based effect. It is important to not confuse this class
with gs.GraphicEffect, which is for own custom shader-based effects. This class is for internal usage
only and encapsulates the OpenGL shader program. You should not create instance of this class manually.

gs.TextureFilter.name: gs.TextureFilter
gs.TextureFilter.description: Describes different kind of texture filters.

gs.Texture2D.name: gs.Texture2D
gs.Texture2D.description:
A class to deal with textures. This class has a lot of more functions and properties than actually documented. That is because this class is actually for internal usage only. The only exception is if you work with custom GLSL shaders.

If you want to learn more about why certain classes of the Basic Engine are hidden and not editable, read the Basic Engine chapter in Help File.

gs.Font.name: gs.Font
gs.Font.description:
A class to describe fonts. Fonts can be loaded from installed
fonts or from imported fonts. (Graphics/Fonts)

params.name: name
params.description: - The font name.

params.name: size
params.description: - The font size in pixels.

gs.Bitmap.name: gs.Bitmap
gs.Bitmap.description:
The bitmap class allows to load images from files or creating in-memory bitmap. It offers different methods to directly draw to the bitmap or recolor it. You can attach a bitmap to a gs.Sprite object to display it on screen.

All bitmaps which are loaded from image files are immutable by default to keep memory usage as low as possible. The pixel-data of an immutable bitmap cannot be changed and the bitmap cannot be drawn onto another bitmap. However, an immutable bitmap will be automatically turned into a mutable bitmap whenever you try to draw onto that bitmap or use it as a source-bitmap. A mutable bitmap may take the double/triple amount of memory compared to an immutable one.

You can make a bitmap immutable/mutable manually anytime using the makeMutable/makeImmutable methods. Notice that a conversion from immutable to mutable or vice-versa may be time-consuming.

params.name: width/filePath/image
params.description: - The width of the bitmap for in-memory creation OR the filePath to an image resource to load it from file OR an HTMLImageElement to create the bitmap from.

params.name: height/languageCode
params.description: - The height of the bitmap OR the language code if the bitmap is created from filePath.

gs.GraphicObject.name: gs.GraphicObject
gs.GraphicObject.description:
The base class of all graphical object. Each graphic object is automatically
rendered and sorted by it z-value.

gs.Video.name: gs.Video
gs.Video.description:
Allows to display videos on screen. The supported video formats depends on the
platform. Only WEBM is supported right now.

params.name: filePath
params.description: - The path to the video resource.

params.name: languageCode
params.description: - The language code to load the video resource depending on language.

gs.Viewport.name: gs.Viewport
gs.Viewport.description:
A viewport manages a list of graphic objects and automatically renders
them ordered by z-index. All graphic object outside of the viewport's bounds
are clipped.

params.name: x|rect
params.description: - The x-coordinate of the viewport's rect OR the whole viewport-rect.

params.name: y
params.description: - The y-coordinate of the viewport's rect.

params.name: width
params.description: - The width of the viewport's rect.

params.name: height
params.description: - The height of the viewport's rect.

gs.BlendMode.name: gs.BlendMode
gs.BlendMode.description: Describes different kind of standard blend modes.

gs.GraphicEffectType.name: gs.GraphicEffectType
gs.GraphicEffectType.description: Describes different kind of shader-based graphic-effect types.

gs.GraphicEffect.name: gs.GraphicEffect
gs.GraphicEffect.description:
The base class of all shader-based graphic effect. If you want to create an own custom
graphic effect you have to inherit from this class. See Effects > CircularDistortionEffect in
Script Editor for an example.

gs.WobbleEffect.name: gs.WobbleEffect
gs.WobbleEffect.description:
Describes a wobble-effect. A wobble-effects animates the texture-coordinates
using sin/cos functions to generate a "wobble"-like effect.

gs.BlurEffect.name: gs.BlurEffect
gs.BlurEffect.description: Describes a blur-effect which blurs the screen using LOD.

gs.PixelateEffect.name: gs.PixelateEffect
gs.PixelateEffect.description: Describes a pixelate-effect which pixelates the game object.

gs.Mask.name: gs.Mask
gs.Mask.description: Stores mask-settings for masking-effects. There are two types of masking, static and dynamic. Static masking just applies the mask to the target using the vague. Dynamic masking applies the mask depending on the value property. For more info about masking, see help.file.

params.name: data
params.description: - Optional data-bundle to create the motion-blur settings from.

params.name: data
params.description: - Optional data-bundle to create the motion-blur settings from.

gs.Sprite.name: gs.Sprite
gs.Sprite.description:
A sprite displays a bitmap or video on screen. It also supports different kind of
visual effects like zooming, rotating, tinting, etc.

params.name: viewport
params.description: - The viewport.

params.name: viewport
params.description: - The viewport. Defaults to gs.Graphics.viewport.

gs.TilingSprite.name: gs.TilingSprite
gs.TilingSprite.description:
A tiling sprite tiles a bitmap or video over the screen. It also supports different kind of
visual effects like tinting, blending, etc.

params.name: viewport
params.description: - The viewport.

params.name: managed
params.description: - Indicates if the sprite should be managed by the graphic-system.

gs.Live2DModel.name: gs.Live2DModel
gs.Live2DModel.description:
This class is used to load a Live2D model from .live2d archive. See Resource Standards in Help File for
more information.

params.name: filePath
params.description: - The path to the Live2D resource.

params.name: languageCode
params.description: - The language code to load the Live2D resource depending on language.

gs.Live2DMotionPlayTypes.name: gs.Live2DMotionPlayTypes
gs.Live2DMotionPlayTypes.description: Enumeration of different Live2D motion-group play types.

gs.Live2DMotionManager.name: gs.Live2DMotionManager
gs.Live2DMotionManager.description: Manages Live2D motions and plays them on a model.

gs.Live2DObject.name: gs.Live2DObject
gs.Live2DObject.description: Displays an associated Live2D model on screen.

params.name: viewport
params.description: - The viewport.

gs.TilesetConfiguration.name: gs.TilesetConfiguration
gs.TilesetConfiguration.description:
A tileset configuration is used for gs.Tilemap to describe the structure of the tileset. For more
info, check out the "Tilemaps" chapter in "Scripter's Guide" in help-file.

params.name: tileSize
params.description:
- The size of a single tile on the tileset. A single tile needs to be quadratic so a value of 32
means 32x32 pixels. If omitted, a value of 32 is used.

gs.Tilemap.name: gs.Tilemap
gs.Tilemap.description:
A tilemap can be used to display the environment of a level/map of a game. For more information
about how to use tilemaps, features and limitations please read the "Scripter's Guide" in the help-file.

params.name: viewport
params.description: - The viewport to associate the tilemap with.

gs.TilemapLayer.name: gs.TilemapLayer
gs.TilemapLayer.description:
A tilemap layer is used to display a single layer of a gs.Tilemap. It is not recommended to use this class directly. For more information
about how to use tilemaps, features and limitations please read the "Scripter's Guide" in the help-file.

params.name: viewport
params.description: - The viewport to associate the tilemap layer with.

params.name: tilemap
params.description: - The tilemap to associate the tilemap layer with.

params.name: width
params.description: - The width of the layer in tiles.

params.name: height
params.description: - The height of the layer in tiles.

params.name: mapData
params.description: - The map-data for the layer.

params.name: tileSize
params.description: - The tile-size of this layer.

params.name: tilesetBitmap
params.description: - The tileset to use.

params.name: animationSpeed
params.description: - The animation speed for animated tiles. (The duration in frames before next pattern is displayed)

gs.ThreePartImage.name: gs.ThreePartImage
gs.ThreePartImage.description:
A three-part image is rendered using three sub-images: start, middle and end. The start and end will be rendered with fixed size while the middle-part will be stretched in a way like this:

|Start-Part Fixed|<-----------Middle-Part Stretched----------->|End-Part Fixed

A three-part image is automatically added to the graphics-system and rendered every frame until it gets disposed. It can be horizontal or vertical.

gs.Frame.name: gs.Frame
gs.Frame.description:
A frame useful to create in-game UI elements like buttons or windows. For more information
about the frame skin-graphic see help-file. A frame is automatically added to the graphics-system
and rendered every frame until it gets disposed.

params.name: viewport
params.description: - The viewport.

classitems.description:
Indicates if no internal tileset should be created and the original tileset image should be used as is. In that case, the expandedSize, regularTiles and specialTiles properties have no effect. In addition, gs.Tilemap.autotiles are ignored too and no autotile expansion will happen. You have to prepare the original tileset image yourself.

Notice that this is set to true by default.

classitems.description:
Defines the area on the tileset used for special tiles such as auto/terrain or animated tiles. It is important that the y-coordinate of this area is always 0 and the height should match the tileset height or should be dividable by the special tile height.

Only the x-coordinate and width can be configured. The more the x-coordinate is moved to the right, the the more space becomes available for regular tiles. But in exchange for that, the space for animation-frames becomes less. So if you don't use animated tiles at all, you can move the x-coordinate completely to right.

There is technically no difference between an auto/terrain or animated tile. Only one kind of special tiles is supported per tileset. For Example: If you decide to use auto/terrain tile taking 256x192 pixels in expanded state, you cannot have 32x32 animated tiles in addition. In that case, your animated tiles need to be auto/terrain tiles as well with 256x192 offset per animation frame. That kind of limitation is necessary for optimization on mobile devices.
classitems.name: specialTiles

classitems.description:
Defines the size of a special/animated tile. For normal animated tiles, this size is just the regular tile size. But for auto or terrain tiles, this is the size of the expanded auto/terrain-tileset and not of a single tile.

This setting is important to animate auto / terrain tiles correctly. The width is used as the animation-offset.
